text: This report details the 2002 results from an ongoing project to monitor the
label: BODY

text: migration behavior of wild spring/summer chinook salmon smolts in the Snake River
label: BODY

text: Basin.  The report also discusses trends in the cumulative data collected for this project
label: BODY

text: from Oregon and Idaho streams since 1989.
label: BODY

text: The project was initiated after detection data from passive-integrated-transponder
label: BODY

text: tags (PIT tags) had shown distinct differences in migration patterns between wild and
label: BODY

text: hatchery fish for three consecutive years.  National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS)
label: BODY

text: investigators first observed these differences in 1989.  The data originated from tagging
label: BODY

text: and interrogation operations begun in 1988 to evaluate smolt transportation for the U.S.
label: BODY

text: In 1991, the Bonneville Power Administration began a cooperative effort with

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: migration patterns would emerge, and to investigate the influence of environmental
label: BODY

text: factors on the timing and distribution of these migrations.

text: We have observed a 2- to 3-week shift in timing of combined wild stocks passing
label: BODY

text: Lower Granite Dam between relatively warm and relatively cold years.  In the warm
label: BODY

text: years of 1990, 1992, 1994, 1998, and 2001 the median passage date at the dam was
label: BODY

text: between 29 April and 9 May, and the 90th percentile of all wild fish passed by the end of
label: BODY

text: May.  In the cold years of 1989, 1991, and 1993, median passage did not occur until
label: BODY

text: mid-May, and the 90th percentile had not passed until mid-June (except during high
label: BODY

text: flows in 1993, when the 90th percentile passed by the end of May).  In both 1992 and
label: BODY

text: 2001, we experienced near record low flows in the Snake River.  The overall migration
label: BODY

text: timing patterns of wild fish at the dam were similar in these two years; however, the
label: BODY

text: timing in 1992 was earlier than 2001 due to the very warm spring in 1992.
label: BODY

text: In 1995, weather conditions in late winter and early spring were moderate
label: BODY

text: compared to those of the previous six years, and we observed intermediate passage
label: BODY

text: timing at the dam relative to previous study years, with the median and 90th percentile
label: BODY

text: passage occurring on 9 May and 5 June, respectively.  In 1996 and 1997, too few Idaho
label: BODY

text: fish were detected to make meaningful comparisons of timing with other years.
label: BODY

text: In 1999, we experienced different climatic conditions than in all previous
label: BODY

text: migration years.  In late winter, a near-record snow pack in the Snake River Basin
label: BODY

text: resulted in high flows during the early spring period (late March); however, the ensuing
label: BODY

text: flows were moderated by very dry and cold conditions during mid-to-late spring and
label: BODY

text: early summer.  The fluctuating medium-to-high flows throughout the spring moved wild
label: BODY

text: fish through Lower Granite Dam as observed in warmer years, with the 50th percentile
label: BODY

text: passing by 3 May and the 90th by 28 May.
label: BODY

text: In 2000, we had more typical temperatures and climatic conditions throughout the
label: BODY

text: spring, along with slightly below-normal flows, with the highest flows occurring in April.
label: BODY

text: Consequently, we observed a wild fish migration pattern similar to those seen in warm
label: BODY

text: years, with the 50th and 90th percentiles passing in early and late May, respectively.  In

text: In 1988, the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) began a cooperative
label: BODY

text: study with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to mark wild Snake River spring and
label: BODY

text: summer chinook salmon parr with passive integrated transponder (PIT) tags for
label: BODY

text: transportation research.  This project continued through mid-1991, with migrating smolts
label: BODY

text: monitored as they passed Lower Granite, Little Goose, and McNary Dams during spring
label: BODY

text: and summer 1989-1991 (Matthews et al. 1990, 1992; Achord et al. 1992, 1996b).
label: BODY

text: Information from these three years of study demonstrated that the migration
label: BODY

text: timing of wild stocks through Lower Granite Dam differs among stream of origin and
label: BODY

text: also differs from the migration timing of hatchery-reared fish.  Migrations of wild spring
label: BODY

text: chinook salmon were consistently later and more protracted than those of their
label: BODY

text: hatchery-reared counterparts, and exhibited more variable timing patterns over the three
label: BODY

text: years.  In contrast, the migrations of wild summer chinook salmon during these same
label: BODY

text: years were earlier, though also more protracted, than those of their hatchery counterparts.

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Length-distribution curves for data collected over the last 14 years have generally
label: BODY

text: shown that wild fish released and subsequently detected at dams are slightly larger at
label: BODY

text: release than fish released but not detected.  The reason for this difference in detection
label: BODY

text: rates is unknown, but we speculated that larger fish survived better than smaller fish.
label: BODY

text: However, Zabel and Achord (in review) compared length, weight, and condition index
label: BODY

text: for these stocks to parr-to-smolt survival over a 5-year period and found that mean
label: BODY

text: population length and weight were not related to survival.  However, year and site effects
label: BODY

text: were detected.  Consistent patterns across years of selection for length and weight were
label: BODY

text: found, but condition factor was selectively neutral.  These results imply that the relative
label: BODY

text: size of individuals within populations was important, but the average size of a population
label: BODY

text: was not, at least in terms of performance during the juvenile life stage.
label: BODY

text: Another consistent trend that has emerged over the years is the difference in
label: BODY

text: arrival timing at Lower Granite Dam with respect to size at release.  In 2002, we again
label: BODY

text: observed that wild fish detected at the dam in April and May had been significantly
label: BODY

text: larger at release than fish migrating after May.  This suggests that size is an important
label: BODY

text: factor related to either the initiation of smoltification or to other life-history dynamics
label: BODY

text: that affect the migration timing of wild fish.

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Raymond (1979) showed that peaks in migration for the composite population of spring
label: BODY

text: and summer chinook salmon smolts (mostly wild) passing Ice Harbor Dam from 1964 to
label: BODY

text: 1969 preceded periods of maximum river discharge in most years.  During these years,
label: BODY

text: fish passage peaked between 26 April and 13 May.  With respect to river flows, our
label: BODY

text: observations matched those of Raymond for wild fish migrating before mid-May.
label: BODY

text: Annual overall climatic variation was thought to be an important factor
label: BODY

text: controlling the overall migrational timing and passage dynamics of wild spring/summer
label: BODY

text: chinook salmon smolts at Lower Granite Dam.  In the warm years of 1990, 1992, 1994,
label: BODY

text: 1998, and 2001, the median passage date at the dam was between 29 April and 9 May,
label: BODY

text: and the 90th percentile of all wild fish passed by the end of May.  In the cold years of
label: BODY

text: 1989, 1991, and 1993, median passage did not occur until mid-May, and the 90th
label: BODY

text: percentile had not passed until mid-June (except during high flows in 1993, when the
label: BODY

text: 90th percentile passed by the end of May).
label: BODY

text: Within these 8 years, we saw a consistent 2- to 3-week shift in timing of wild fish
label: BODY

text: at the dam between relatively warm and relatively cold years.  In 1995, intermediate
label: BODY

text: weather conditions prevailed in late winter and early spring (compared to the previous
label: BODY

text: six years), and we observed intermediate passage times of 9 May and 5 June for the 50th
label: BODY

text: and 90th percentile passage dates, respectively, for these combined wild populations.
label: BODY

text: In 1999, we experienced different climatic conditions than in all previous
label: BODY

text: migration years.  In late winter, a near-record snow pack in the Snake River Basin
label: BODY

text: resulted in high flows early in the migration period (during late March); however, the
label: BODY

text: ensuing flows were moderated by very dry and cold conditions during the remaining
label: BODY

text: spring and early summer.  Fluctuating, medium-to-high flows throughout the spring
label: BODY

text: moved the wild fish through Lower Granite Dam as observed in warmer years, with the
label: BODY

text: 50th percentile passing by 3 May and the 90th by 28 May (Achord et al. 2001a).  Flows
label: BODY

text: during 2000 were slightly below normal, with highest flows occurring in April, along
label: BODY

text: with more seasonal temperatures and climatic conditions throughout the spring.
label: BODY

text: Consequently, we observed a wild fish migration pattern similar to a warm year, with
label: BODY

text: 50th percentile passing by 6 May and the 90th by 29 May.
label: BODY

text: In 2002, the 50th and 90th percentiles of wild fish also passed Lower Granite
label: BODY

text: Dam in early and late May, respectively.  However, in 2002, we had slightly lower than
label: BODY

text: normal temperatures and cooler than normal conditions throughout the spring, along with
label: BODY

text: close to normal flows, with the highest flows occurring in mid-April and late-May.
label: BODY

text: Therefore, although our previous observations support the importance of annual climatic
label: BODY

text: conditions influencing overall migration timing of the stocks at Lower Granite Dam,
label: BODY

text: clearly, complex interrelationships of several factors drives the annual migrational timing
label: BODY

text: The migration timing of individual wild stocks has been highly variable and
label: BODY

text: usually protracted at Lower Granite Dam.  However, migration-timing patterns emerging
label: BODY

text: for some stocks range from early to late spring.  Shifts in timing of passage distribution
label: BODY

text: for these stocks have been less than 1 to 5 weeks over all years, and these shifts appear
label: BODY

text: related to annual climatic conditions and probably several other factors.
label: BODY

text: An important objective of this study is to examine the migration timing at Lower
label: BODY

text: Granite Dam of individual stocks over a period of years to determine similarities or
label: BODY

text: differences between years and between stocks.  We now have at least nine years of
label: BODY

text: migration-timing data for fish from 10 of the study streams, and this allowed us to
label: BODY

text: construct 95% confidence intervals for the 10th, 50th, and 90th percentile passage dates
label: BODY

text: at Lower Granite Dam for fish from these streams (Table 8).

text: In examining wild chinook salmon smolt passage timing at the dams over the last
label: BODY

text: 14 years, it has become clear that several factors influence passage timing.  Complex
label: BODY

text: yearly interrelationships between flow and annual climatic conditions are primary factors
label: BODY

text: contributing to passage timing.  However, water temperature, turbidity, physiological
label: BODY

text: development, variability in stock behavior, fish size, and other yet unknown factors may
label: BODY

text: all contribute substantially to wild smolt passage timing at dams.
label: BODY

text: As additional environmental monitors and traps are installed in study streams, we
label: BODY

text: can more accurately monitor fry, parr, and smolt movements out of rearing areas and
label: BODY

text: examine the relationships between these movements and environmental conditions within
label: BODY

text: the streams.  Mapped over time, this information, along with weather and climate data,
label: BODY

text: will provide tools for the accurate prediction of movement in different wild stocks.  Such
label: BODY

text: tools are vital to recovery planning for threatened or endangered species of Pacific
